          "body": "Verse 11 is the chapter's most personal address: 'Be wise, my son, and make my heart glad, that I may reply to him who reproaches me.' The father-sage speaks with skin in the game — his own reputation is partly carried by his son's wisdom or folly. This is not mere reputation management; it reflects the ancient understanding that wisdom is transmitted through relationship, and the teacher is honored or shamed by whether the teaching took root. Verse 12 describes the prudent man (arum — shrewd, perceptive) who sees evil coming and hides himself, while the simple (peti — naively open, easily enticed) walk into it and pay the penalty. Prudence is not paranoia; it is the capacity to read trajectories before they arrive. Verse 22 closes the chapter's fool-portrait with one of Proverbs' most unsparing images: you may pound a fool in a mortar with a pestle, grinding him along with crushed grain, and his foolishness will not depart from him. The image captures what modern psychology would call character-settled pathology — the intervention is as extreme as imaginable, and still the folly remains. The sage is not cruel; he is realistic. Some people are not improved by correction, and wisdom requires knowing the difference between the one who will receive a wound faithfully and the one who cannot."
