          "title": "The insatiable eye and the testing furnace (27:19-21)",
          "body": "Verses 19-21 form a tight trio of character-diagnostic sayings that culminate in the chapter's most incisive test. Verse 19 establishes the principle: as water reflects a face, so the heart reflects the man. The heart (lev — the whole inner life) is the true mirror. What you really are is visible in your heart, not your performance. Verse 20 applies the principle to desire: the eyes of man are never satisfied, just as Sheol and Abaddon are never full. The comparison to the realm of the dead is arresting — to live with insatiable acquisitive desire is to live in a death-like state, consuming endlessly without satisfaction (cf. Ecclesiastes 1:8; 4:8; 5:10-11). Then verse 21 names the test that reveals whether the heart is genuinely formed or merely performing: the crucible tests silver, the furnace tests gold, and praise tests a man. The furnace analogy is drawn from the metallurgical world — the crucible does not create purity; it reveals what is already there. Praise is the furnace. How a person handles commendation — whether it inflates, whether it is deflected with false modesty, whether it is received with honest gratitude — shows the interior reality that verse 19 named as the true mirror of the self."
