        "excerpt": "Do not boast about tomorrow, for you do not know what a day may bring forth. Let another praise you, and not your own mouth.",
        "body": "The double-opening of Proverbs 27 is more theologically dense than its brevity suggests. The prohibition against boasting about tomorrow is grounded in an epistemological limit — you do not know what a day will give birth to (*yalad*). This is not mere practical caution but a wisdom-tradition confession of human creatureliness: the future belongs to God (Proverbs 16:1, 9; 19:21). The same logic animates James 4:13-17, which draws directly from this wisdom tradition: the person who says 'today or tomorrow we will go to such and such a city' has forgotten that he is a vapor. Boasting about tomorrow is not just imprudent; it is a failure to reckon with God as the one who holds the future.\n\nVerse 2 extends the same posture inward: do not praise yourself. Self-praise (*halal* turned reflexive) is the relational form of the same arrogance — claiming superior knowledge of your own worth. The instruction to let a stranger (nokhri — an outsider, not a family member) evaluate you rather than your own lips is radical. It transfers the seat of judgment from the self to the community. Paul applies the same logic in 2 Corinthians 10:17-18: 'Let the one who boasts, boast in the Lord. For it is not the one who commends himself who is approved, but the one whom the Lord commends.'\n\nThe pairing of these two proverbs at the chapter's head is not accidental. Both target the same root disposition — the pretension to knowledge and authority the self does not actually possess. The boaster about tomorrow pretends to know the future; the self-praiser pretends to be the most reliable evaluator of himself. Wisdom begins by surrendering both pretensions.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Halal* (27:1, 2, 21) — to boast, praise, commend. Its threefold appearance in this chapter ties together the opening prohibition (27:1), the command about self-praise (27:2), and the furnace-test of praise received (27:21). *Yalad* — 'may bring forth' — uses the birth verb; the day is pregnant with unknown contents. *Nokhri* — a stranger outside the family, whose assessment is more objective precisely because he has no relational interest in flattering you."
