        "title": "The weight of folly, the fire of jealousy — diagnosing social destructiveness",
        "range": "27:3-4",
        "excerpt": "The provocation of a fool is heavier than both of them. But who can stand before jealousy?",
        "body": "These two proverbs are not primarily about the fool or the jealous person — they are about what it costs to live near them. The fool's provocation (*kaas* — vexation, grief-causing irritation) is measured against the heaviest things in the material world. Stone and sand do not give way under their own weight; they must be carried. The fool's provocation is heavier still. This is the wisdom tradition's honest reckoning with the social cost of proximity to the morally obtuse: it is not merely unpleasant; it is exhausting in a way that exceeds the imagination of someone who has not experienced it.\n\nVerse 4 escalates the scale. Wrath (*chemah* — burning heat, fury) and anger (*aph* — the snorting, inflamed nose) are already pictured as extreme — fierce, a flood. Yet both are outdone by jealousy (*qinah*). The rhetorical question 'who can stand before jealousy?' expects no answer. *Qinah* is the passion that possesses its host entirely. In the narrative backdrop of Proverbs — the portrait of Solomon whose wisdom failed to protect him — it is ultimately his failure to guard his heart from the competing jealousies of his foreign wives (1 Kings 11:1-11) that unravels the kingdom. Proverbs 6:34 warns that a jealous husband's fury cannot be appeased even by restitution; the same consuming quality here threatens anyone who enters its field.\n\nPastorally, the wisdom these two proverbs offer is permission to name the cost accurately. The sage does not tell the reader to simply endure the fool or the jealous rival with equanimity — he tells the reader what they are actually dealing with. Accurate diagnosis precedes wise response. Peter Davids notes in a related context (James 3:13-4:2) that the wisdom tradition consistently treats disordered desire (*qinah* and *epithumia*) as the source of communal destruction, and its naming is the beginning of resistance.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Kaas* — irritation, vexation, the emotion produced in others by the fool. *Chemah* — burning fury; *aph* — lit. 'nostril,' the physiological site of snorting rage. *Qinah* — jealousy or consuming zeal; the same word used positively of God's jealousy for His people (Exodus 20:5) but here at its most destructive human register."
